<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION SOCCER PREVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
HAMPTON BOOSTS TEAMMATES; 
</P>
<P>
SOCCER: ALL-AMERICAN MIDFIELDER HAS BROUGHT THE ABILITIES OF SIMI VALLEY 
PLAYERS TO ANOTHER LEVEL. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE GLAZE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After Craig Hampton was selected to the 1989 All-American soccer team earlier 
this month, some of his Simi Valley High teammates were awed by the senior 
midfielder's presence. 
</P>
<P>
But now the Pioneers have not only accepted Hampton's recognition by the 
National Soccer Coaches Assn. of America but some of his skills have begun to 
rub off on his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
"Some kids, when playing with a national-level player on their team, don't 
really shy away from him, they're a little intimidated," Simi Valley Coach Andy 
Silva said. "That intimidation carries right onto the field. We had a couple of 
players like that . . . it's sort of fading away now." 
</P>
<P>
Silva stressed that playing alongside Hampton has helped his teammates hone 
their own techniques. 
</P>
<P>
"Of (Hampton's) play and ability, it has brought the other kids' ability up to 
play top-level soccer," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Top-level soccer has been a trademark of Simi Valley teams. 
</P>
<P>
The Pioneers have won seven Marmonte League championships this decade, 
including two three-year reigns from 1980-82 and 1984-86. They finished second 
in the Southern Section 4-A Division in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
This year, Simi Valley is ranked second behind defending 4-A champion Palos 
Verdes; Marmonte teams Royal and Newbury Park are ranked seventh and ninth. 
</P>
<P>
"I think we have a good chance of going a long way in the 4-A," the 11th-year 
coach said, "but I don't want to count my chickens before they're hatched." 
</P>
<P>
Eight players return for Simi Valley -- including seven starters -- from last 
year's team that advanced to the 4-A quarterfinals before losing to Hawthorne, 
2-0. 
</P>
<P>
Hampton, senior midfielder Andre Markarian and junior striker Brian Weaver lead 
a potent Pioneer offense. 
</P>
<P>
In its first eight matches, Simi Valley is averaging 3.75 goals. 
</P>
<P>
Weaver has been equally effective at goal-scoring as well as feeding assists. 
Senior forward Kenny Greninger also is a frequent contributor. 
</P>
<P>
Simi Valley recorded five consecutive shutouts to start the season as 
goalkeepers Angelo Maccano and Mike Jones, a sophomore, shared time. 
</P>
<P>
Defenders Sean Kieldrup and Marc Cargnel head the Valley area's stingiest 
defense, which did not allow a goal in the Pioneers' first six games. 
</P>
<P>
Other teams to watch: 
</P>
<P>
Channel Islands -- After a season in which the Raiders won only three matches, 
first-year Coach Al Tarazon has the Raiders playing well. 
</P>
<P>
Channel Islands is off to a 6-1-1 record and senior goalkeeper Rosario Pina has 
posted four shutouts. 
</P>
<P>
Sophomore Oscar Gutierrez and freshman Francisco Leon provide punch at forward 
for the a team dominated by underclassmen, and senior Victor Martinez and 
junior Jose Sarabia, both halfbacks, add depth. 
</P>
<P>
Senior twins Gabriel and German Prieto and juniors Lupe Moreno and Francisco 
Robles are key defenders. 
</P>
<P>
Royal -- After winning the 4-A title in the 1987-88 season and missing the 
playoffs the following year, the Highlanders again are on the upswing, starting 
the season 6-0-1. 
</P>
<P>
Senior striker Matt Brinkman, a dangerous offensive player, scored a hat trick 
Thursday in a 3-2 win over Santa Paula. 
</P>
<P>
Sophomore goalkeeper Steven Hambly is the cornerstone of Royal's defense along 
with Michael Hansen and Daniel Anderson 
</P>
<P>
Marco Todesco is a quarterback-type player, setting up offensive plays from his 
midfielder position along with midfielder Kai Schraml. 
</P>
<P>
St. Francis -- First-year Coach Glen Appels inherited the defending Del Rey 
League titlist that went 16-1-1 last year and reached the semifinals of the 3-A 
playoffs before falling to eventual champion Mission Viejo. 
</P>
<P>
Nine players return, most of whom saw limited action. 
</P>
<P>
Senior David Beall scored six goals in this season's first five games from his 
midfielder position, and senior midfielder Erik Franken provides depth. 
</P>
<P>
Appels said that the Golden Knights' strength lies in their defense, for which 
he has two solid performers in defender Matthew Hydar and midfielder Mike 
Rendon, both seniors. 
</P>
<P>
Burroughs -- Although they had a less-than-stellar season in 1989, Mike 
Kodama's Indians have 11 players back. The addition of two forwards and a 
sweeper from last year's 16-1-2 junior varsity should spark Burroughs in the 
nine-team Foothill League. 
</P>
<P>
Burroughs compiled a 7-9-4 record and finished fifth in league play at 4-6-4. 
But with veteran players the Indians, behind their third-year coach, are 
already pushing good teams. They were edged recently by defending 1-A champion 
La Canada, 3-2, in a nonleague game. 
</P>
<P>
All-league defender Carlos Roque, a junior, is in the backfield along with 
sophomore sweeper Ian Goyanes, up from the junior varsity. 
</P>
<P>
Seniors Sean O'Connor and Jeff Gierok, both third-year players, will lead the 
Indians' offense from their midfielder and forward positions. Senior forwards 
Octavio Alejandres and Jason Pitkin will provide additional support. 
</P>
<P>
L. A. Baptist -- Eleven players return for the Knights -- including eight 
starters -- from the team that lost in the quarterfinals of the 1989 Small 
Schools Division playoffs to eventual champion Morro Bay. 
</P>
<P>
Senior midfielder Ron Simpson, an All-Southern Section selection, scored 16 
goals and had 14 assists in leading L. A. Baptist to a 17-6-1 record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
